{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658174","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658174"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:44:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:44:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20716"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20716","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20716"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.87,0,0.09,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13592"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95819"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13592","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13592"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20716"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78598"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11587"},{"type":"tags","id":"12520"},{"type":"tags","id":"12595"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32682"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32683"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95819","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/95819"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThrombus formation in arteries differs significantly from venous thrombosis in both mechanism and composition.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the pathophysiology of thrombus formation in the arterial circulation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Decreased thrombomodulin expression with stasis","Endothelial injury with platelet activation","Increased tissue plasminogen activator release","Reduced blood flow with fibrin accumulation","Enhanced protein C pathway activation"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003Eendothelial injury with platelet activation\u003C/strong\u003E. Endothelial injury is a critical initiating event in arterial thrombosis, leading to platelet adherence and activation. This is particularly important in high shear stress environments like arteries, where platelets are necessary for thrombus formation. The resulting thrombi in arterial and cardiac circulation are characteristically platelet-rich.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased thrombomodulin expression with stasis\u003C/strong\u003E - While thrombomodulin is decreased during endothelial activation, stasis is not a primary mechanism in arterial thrombosis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduced blood flow with fibrin accumulation\u003C/strong\u003E - This better describes venous thrombosis. Arterial thrombi form despite high flow rates\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnhanced protein C pathway activation\u003C/strong\u003E - Protein C has anticoagulant effects and is actually decreased during endothelial activation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased tissue plasminogen activator release\u003C/strong\u003E - During endothelial activation, tissue plasminogen activator expression is downregulated, not increased\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEndothelial activation creates a prothrombotic state through both procoagulant changes and antifibrinolytic effects.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Endothelial injury leading to platelet activation is a key mechanism in arterial and cardiac thrombus formation.","Arterial and cardiac thrombi are typically platelet-rich due to the high shear stress environment.","Endothelial activation or dysfunction creates a prothrombotic state through procoagulant changes and antifibrinolytic effects."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 4; page 126."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78598"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20716"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78598","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/78598"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-29T20:41:04+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-29T20:42:32+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13592"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95819"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11587","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11587"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Haemodynamic disorders: thromboembolic disease and shock","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":3,"createdAt":"2025-02-26T15:17:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-26T15:17:52+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"18"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12520","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12520"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Thrombosis","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2025-03-23T12:01:55+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-23T12:01:55+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"10"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12595","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12595"},"attributes":{"e